creator: idea.hatchery@rutgers.edu (Innovation, Design, and Entrepreneurship Academy)
title: Design Challenge (Cancelled)
author: idea.hatchery@rutgers.edu (Innovation, Design, and Entrepreneurship Academy)
content:
Design Challenge

On March 25th, the IDEA program will be kicking off a Design Challenge in collaboration with the Rutgers Center for Adult Autism Services and Prophet.  This design challenge is a mentored problem-solving experience that occurs over a 6-week period.  

 

The challenge theme is: How might we envision an inclusive campus climate to support the neurodiversity of Rutgers students, faculty, and staff?

 

The six weeks are going to work towards creating a "Future States" solution where you will work with physical materials (images, text, art, etc.) to create a shared vision for future experiences at Rutgers. If you are looking for a non-tech design experience, this design challenge will be more on the creative side, so it could be perfect for you!

 

No previous design experience is needed.  During the challenge you will work with professional Designers/Innovation Consultants to:

*Learn to conduct interviews and develop actionable insights
*Learn Design Principles
*Develop Future State Scenario solutions
*Discuss solution sustainability

If you are interested in this design challenge, please use this registration link to sign up!

From Friday, April 29, 2022 10:00 AM to 12:00 PM EDT at Rutgers Center for Adult Autism Services.

creator: diversityatdouglass@echo.rutgers.edu (Douglass Diversity and Inclusion Program at Douglass Residential College - DRC)
title: Ecofeminism Presentation By DEI Ambassadors
author: diversityatdouglass@echo.rutgers.edu (Douglass Diversity and Inclusion Program at Douglass Residential College - DRC)
content:
Ecofeminism Presentation By DEI Ambassadors

Please join us and come to an event hosted by the Douglass Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion Ambassadors! The ambassadors will present their semester-long research presentation where attendees will learn how the climate crisis and women's rights are interconnected, define what ecofeminism means, identify activists/poets who have been instrumental in the ecofeminist movement and what contributions they made to it, and understand at least one way that ecofeminism is relevant to today–be it politically, environmentally, economically, etc. Students should attend to learn about a topic that is not widely talked about during a crucial time - we are currently going through a climate crisis and the rights of women are being attacked. Learn how these two current problems intersect and what you can do about them.

From Friday, April 29, 2022 4:00 PM to 5:00 PM EDT at Kathleen W. Ludwig Classroom 008.

title: RUSEPRC Barkyard Bonding
author: ruseprc.secretary@gmail.com (Seeing Eye Puppy Raising Club (Rutgers University))
content:
RUSEPRC Barkyard Bonding
We kicked off this year with a picnic in the Barkyard and we'll be ending this year in the same fashion! Stop by the Barkyard on Cook Campus any time between 12 and 3 to hang out with the puppies! This event is extremely casual and low-key. Members will get the chance to hang out with each other and the puppies before summer break! This may be your last chance to see the puppies who are graduating from RUSEPRC along with their raisers :(.  We will be providing snacks, water, and some good tunes. 
 
Important information:
  • Puppies of any age may attend provided they are healthy and confident
  • Club attire is not required
  • **Only two off-leash puppies are permitted per run (must also have the permission of both raisers that their dogs can play together)
  • Please DO NOT leave your trash in the Barkyard!
  • Be mindful of any food spills in the Barkyard: if you notice any, clean it up. If you notice a dog eating things they are not supposed to, intervene immediately and/or notify a raiser at once
  • Be mindful of closing any gates after you enter/leave through them 
  • Remember: closed-toe shoes are required if you want to handle our puppies
Please find an eBoard member to get your attendance taken!
 
Click here to fill out the form if you are attending
Click here to see the puppies that are attending

From Sunday, May 1, 2022 12:00 PM to 3:00 PM EDT at RUSEPRC Barkyard- Cook Campus.

  • Club attire IS required

creator: rop@echo.rutgers.edu (Rites of Passage Ceremony)
title: 30th Annual Rites of Passage Ceremony Registration
author: rop@echo.rutgers.edu (Rites of Passage Ceremony)
content:
30th Annual Rites of Passage Ceremony Registration

The annual Rites of Passage Ceremony is a pre-commencement celebration to honor Black and Latinx-identified students who through resolute persistence have successfully completed an undergraduate or graduate degree at Rutgers University—New Brunswick. The event recognizes their accomplishments, hard work, and dedication, while simultaneously acknowledging the accomplishments of our student’s families and networks of support. Distinguished speakers, student awards, performances, and the incorporation of African culture and traditions—specifically the culminating Kente Stole presentation—all add to the vibrancy of this celebratory day.

Participation in the Rites of Passage Ceremony is open to all Black and Latinx-identified Rutgers University – New Brunswick Undergraduate and Graduate students who have earned their degree between January 2022 and August 2022. In order to participate, students must register by April 22nd, 2022 through the getINVOLVED portal. Only students who have registered by this date are guaranteed to be listed in the program and receive a kente stole. The late registration deadline is May 1st. All graduates are required to wear their academic regalia, which can be purchased from the Barnes and Noble Rutgers University Bookstore on Somerset Street. There is no cost to participate in Rites of Passage for graduates or guests.

All graduates who register by the April 22nd deadline will receive the following:
-1 Free Kente Cloth Stole
-1 Commemorative T-shirt
-1 Commemorative Program Booklet
-Unlimited number of guests
-Free access to the reception for graduates and guests immediately following ceremony

If you have specific questions about your registration or the ceremony, please email rop@echo.rutgers.edu.

From Wednesday, May 11, 2022 3:00 PM to 5:00 PM EDT at Jersey Mike's Arena.

author: DouglassWiSE@echo.rutgers.edu (Douglass WiSE at Douglass Residential College - DRC)
content:
Douglass-ODASIS DOCTORS Living-Learning Community - Cohort 1

Welcome to the Douglass-ODASIS Community That Offers Resources and Support (DOCTORS) Living-Learning Community for Douglass-ODASIS undergraduate women of color pursuing allied health professional fields. 

The DOCTORS LLC provides a powerful set of programs to advance women in the sciences. Students are surrounded by peers who are experiencing similar changes and successes. Built-in residential support such as mentoring, tutoring, research opportunities and hands-on experiences empower women to persevere and succeed in STEM disciplines and careers. 

DOCTORS residents are encouraged to participate in the programs offered in the residence hall, meet regularly with the Graduate Mentors, and respect the academic environment of the residence hall. Additionally, Bunting-Cobb residents are strongly encouraged to engage in programs sponsored by the Douglass Project and the Douglass Residential College Community.  Becoming an active member of this community and participating in programs will help build your leadership skills, broaden your horizons, and encourage your academic growth.

From Saturday, September 1, 2018 12:00 PM to Sunday, May 15, 2022 12:00 AM EDT at Bunting-Cobb Residence Hall .
